          "body": "The chapter opens with the same three verbs God spoke to Adam — 'be fruitful and multiply and fill the earth' (compare Gen 1:28 and 9:1, 7) — signaling that what follows is not a continuation of the old world but a second creation. The flood has functioned as a de-creation (the waters returned from Gen 1:2); Noah's emergence from the ark is a new-creation event. But the new creation is notably different from the first: animals now fear humans (9:2), flesh is added to the diet (9:3), and an explicit moral law governs bloodshed (9:5-6). These are not upgrades — they are accommodations to a world now irreversibly marked by sin and violence (Gen 6:11). The expansion of dominion and diet is real, but it arrives inside a framework of moral accountability that was not needed before the fall deformed human nature. The ground-level theological claim of this section is 9:6: the prohibition of murder is grounded not in social utility, not in law-code convention, but in the imago Dei. Every human being — without exception of ethnicity, age, status, or utility — bears the tselem of God, and therefore every attack on a human life is an attack on the image of the Creator. This is the biblical foundation for the sanctity of human life, and it precedes the Mosaic law by centuries."
